  "response_text": "Here is a healthy, balanced weekly meal plan designed to be flexible, nutrient-dense, and easy to follow. It focuses on whole foods: lean proteins, healthy fats, complex carbohydrates, and plenty of vegetables.\n\n**Key Principles:**\n- **Hydration:** Drink water, herbal tea, or infused water throughout the day.\n- **Portion Control:** Fill half your plate with vegetables, a quarter with lean protein, and a quarter with whole grains or starchy vegetables.\n- **Prep Ahead:** Wash and chop veggies, cook a batch of quinoa or brown rice, and hard-boil eggs on Sunday.\n\n---\n\n### Weekly Meal Plan\n\n| Day       | Breakfast                                    | Lunch                                            | Dinner                                            | Snack (Optional)                     |\n| :-------- | :------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ | :----------------------------------- |\n| **Monday**  | Greek yogurt with berries, a sprinkle of chia seeds & almonds | Large salad with mixed greens, grilled chicken, chickpeas, cucumber, bell peppers, and lemon-tahini dressing | Baked salmon with roasted broccoli and sweet potato wedges | Apple slices with 1 tbsp peanut butter |\n| **Tuesday** | Oatmeal made with oats, milk (dairy or plant), topped with sliced banana & walnuts | Leftover salmon and roasted vegetables over a bed of quinoa | Turkey & black bean chili (canned or homemade) with a side salad | A small handful of almonds           |\n| **Wednesday**| 2 scrambled eggs with spinach and 1 slice of whole-grain toast | Leftover turkey chili with a dollop of Greek yogurt and sliced avocado | Stir-fry: shrimp, broccoli, carrots, snap peas, and bell peppers over brown rice | Carrot & celery sticks with hummus   |\n| **Thursday**| Smoothie: spinach, frozen mango, plain kefir, 1 tbsp flaxseed, and a splash of water | Large salad with lentils, chopped veggies, feta cheese, and a simple vinaigrette | Lean pork chop with sautéed kale and roasted butternut squash | A hard-boiled egg                    |\n| **Friday**  | Cottage cheese with sliced peaches and a few chopped pecans | Leftover pork chop, kale, and squash (reheat and enjoy) | Whole-wheat pasta with lean ground turkey, tomato sauce (low-sugar), and a side of steamed green beans | A small pear                         |\n| **Saturday**| 2 whole-grain pancakes (made with minimal added sugar) with fresh berries and a dollop of Greek yogurt | Large veggie & hummus wrap: whole-wheat tortilla, hummus, mixed greens, shredded carrots, bell peppers, and cucumber | Lean sirloin steak (grilled or pan-seared) with roasted asparagus and a baked potato (with skin) | Handful of grapes                    |\n| **Sunday**  | Veggie omelet (mushrooms, onions, bell peppers) with 1 slice of whole-grain toast | \"Buddha bowl\": quinoa, roasted chickpeas, avocado, shredded red cabbage, and a drizzle of tahini dressing | Roasted chicken breast with a giant side of roasted Brussels sprouts and carrots | 1 oz dark chocolate (70%+ cacao)     |\n\n---\n\n### Grocery Shopping List\n\n**Produce:**\n- Berries (fresh or frozen)\n- Bananas\n- Apples\n- Pears\n- Peaches (canned in juice or fresh)\n- Grapes\n- Lemons\n- Avocados\n- Spinach (fresh)\n- Mixed salad greens\n- Kale\n- Broccoli\n- Sweet potatoes\n- Carrots\n- Celery\n- Cucumber\n- Bell peppers (various colors)\n- Snap peas\n- Onions\n- Garlic\n- Mushrooms\n- Butternut squash\n- Asparagus\n- Brussels sprouts\n- Green beans\n- Fresh herbs (optional: parsley, cilantro)\n\n**Protein:**\n- Chicken breast (boneless, skinless)\n- Lean ground turkey (93/7 or 99/1)\n- Salmon fillets\n- Shrimp (raw, peeled, deveined)\n- Lean pork chops\n- Lean sirloin steak\n- Whole chicken (for roasting)\n- Eggs\n- Greek yogurt (plain, unsweetened)\n- Cottage cheese\n- Kefir (plain)\n\n**Pantry & Grains:**\n- Rolled oats\n- Quinoa\n- Brown rice\n- Whole-wheat pasta\n- Whole-grain bread or tortillas\n- Canned chickpeas (low-sodium)\n- Canned black beans (low-sodium)\n- Canned lentils (low-sodium)\n- Canned diced tomatoes (no salt added)\n- Tomato sauce (low-sugar)\n- Chili seasoning (or cumin, chili powder, paprika)\n- Tahini\n- Hummus\n- Almonds (raw, unsalted)\n- Walnuts\n- Pecans\n- Chia seeds\n- Flaxseed (ground)\n- Peanut butter (natural, no added sugar)\n- Olive oil\n- Vinegar (balsamic, apple cider)\n- Salt, pepper, your favorite herbs & spices\n- Dark chocolate (70%+ cacao)\n\n**Dairy/Alternatives (Optional):**\n- Milk (dairy or unsweetened plant-based)\n- Feta cheese (optional)\n\n### Tips for Success:\n1.  **Double Dinner:** When you cook dinner (e.g., salmon, chili, pork chops), intentionally make extra for lunch the next day.\n2.  **Batch Cook:** On Sunday, cook a large batch of quinoa or brown rice, roast a tray of mixed vegetables (broccoli, sweet potatoes, carrots), and hard-boil 4-6 eggs.\n3.  **Listen to Your Body:** Adjust portion sizes based on your hunger, activity level, and goals. This is a template, not a strict rule.\n4.  **Stay Flexible:** Swap days if needed. Use leftovers creatively (e.g., roasted chicken can become salad or a wrap).\n\nEnjoy your healthy week of eating",
